<section xml:id="FUNDAMENTALS-OF-RIGHT-TRIANGLES" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>FUNDAMENTALS OF RIGHT TRIANGLES</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>The sum of all of the angles in any triangle must add up to 180°.</p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="right-angle-triangles">
    <title>Right-Angle Triangles</title>

    <p>
      A <term>right angle</term> triangle means there is one angle that is exactly 90°. 
      The side opposite to the right angle is called the <term>Hypotenuse</term> (C). 
      The hypotenuse is the longest side in the right-angled triangle.
    </p>

    <p>
      For all <term>right angle</term> triangles, you can use the 
      <term>Pythagorean Theorem</term> 
      (<m>C^2 = A^2 + B^2</m>) to solve for unknown lengths.
    </p>
    
    <blockquote>
      <p>
         <term>PYTHAGOREAN THEOREM</term> (<m>C^2 = A^2 + B^2</m>)
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <figure xml:id="fig-right-triangle">
      <caption>
        A right triangle with sides A, B, and hypotenuse C.
      </caption>
      <image source="images\right_triangle_transparent.png" width="40%">
      </image>
    </figure>
    
    <p>
      The names of the variables are irrelevant; you can use any letter to denote any of these. 
      Another way to consider this theorem is:
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        (<m>Hypotenuse^2 = Side^2 + OtherSide^2</m>)
      </p>
    </blockquote>
  </subsection>
</section>